’s powerful rhetoric. She argues that public opinion about issues can only be seen as a messy mixture of culture, politics, and economics—in short, all the things that influence how people live. Herbst deftly pins down contours of public opinion in new ways and explores what endures and what doesn’t in the extraordinarily troubled, polarized, and hyper-mediated present. Before we can ask the most important questions about public opinion in American democracy today, we must reckon yet again with the politics and culture of the 1930s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apublic opinion, politics, America, polling.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107391900 cprintz978022681291540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226813073423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226813073/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075417-9  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-PLWb2021